AB  - Malnutrition is widespread in the developing world. Controversy continues concerning the roles of income, household size, and women's schooling on nutrient demand. Empirical estimates for Nicaragua suggest that income elasticities are small and inversely associated with income levels, there are some economies of scale in household size, the elasticity for women's schooling is higher than those for income or household size, and women's backgrounds are important. The results cast doubt on the strong emphasis the World Bank and others have placed on income and suggest that schooling may be working through tastes, not only through productivity.
