AB  - The aim of this paper is to investigate the role played by international influences, exchange rates and expectations in the inflationary process of Greece over the period 1972.I–1981.IV. A theoretical model of determination for small open economics is used which includes both world and domestic influences. In the estimation of the model we assume adaptive, extrapolative and rational expectations. The model explains satisfactorily the behaviour of price inflation in Greece during the 1970s. The major determinants of price inflation are foreign prices, excess demand, unit labour costs, exchange rates and extrapolative price expectations.
