DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(84)90050-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387884900506
AB  - This paper deals with the relationship between money and output in sixteen Latin American countries. Making use of the framework of analysis elaborated by Robert Barro for the United States, three closely interrelated hypotheses are tested: (1) that the growth of the money supply is predictable in that it differs from a random walk with trend; (2) that only the part of money growth which is not predicted will affect real output in the short run; and (3) that, as Lucas has argued, the slope of the Phillips curve is smaller in size for countries where money and prices are less predictable.
