AB  - This paper analyzes the short-run effects of traditional balance-of-payments policies for a small developing country. The country is assumed to be running persistent payments deficits under a fixed exchange rate regime. This paper illustrates how conventional results are affected by the presence of (a) imported intermediate inputs, (b) partial wage indexation, and (c) a large initial trade deficit. Stagflationary effects of a currency devaluation are particularly noteworthy. A tariff/subsidy policy that leaves the price of imported inputs unaffected is shown to be likely to achieve the payments objectives without creating significant adverse supply-side effects.
